The expression imi derisor lecti has been much misunderstood. In order to comprehend its true meaning, we must bear in mind that the buffoons or jesters at a Roman entertainment were placed on the lowest couch along with the entertainer3 (consult note on Sat. 11. viii. 403) and hence derisor imi lecti does not by any means imply, as some sup- pose, a rallier of those who recline on the lowest 0011011, but is merely intended as a general designation for the buffoon or jester of the party. Horace advances a general proposition, and, to make flatterers appear the more odious, he says very judiciously, that in pushing their com- plaisance too far, they degenerate into mere buffoons.—ll. ,Sic ‘rt-utum divitis horret. ‘¹ Is so fearfully attentive to every nod of his patron.'' —14.
